Are you sure we should treat an <i>abstract class</i> as a pure <i>interface</i> here? If so, then we have to rename `BaseDataframePartition -> IDataFramePartition/DataFramePartitionInterface` as it's not a base class anymore. 

Personally, I don't like this approach as it will force us to declare yet another class when we would actually need to create a base partition class (which would bloat our namespace).

<details><summary>Example</summary>

```python
# ====== Pure interface approach =======
class IClass(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def implementation_specific_method(self):
        """BaseClass API that has no common implementation."""
        pass

class BaseClass(IClass): # This class is still abstract
    def generic_method(self):
        """
        Still BaseClass API but already has an implementation that is suitable for
        every descendant. Could be overridden in order to achieve better performance.
        """
        res = self.implementation_specific_method()
        return common_postprocessing(res)

# ====== No interface approach =======
class BaseClass(ABC):
    @abstractmethod
    def implementation_specific_method(self):
        """BaseClass API that has no common implementation."""
        pass

    def generic_method(self):
        """
        Still BaseClass API but already has an implementation that is suitable for
        every descendant. Could be overridden in order to achieve better performance.
        """
        res = self.implementation_specific_method()
        return common_postprocessing(res)
```

</details>

